{code}

Sometimes database errors make pull request merged but then no merge activity within pull request stored into database (timeout or something else).

{code}
mysql> select count(1) from sta_pr_activity a join sta_pr_merge_activity ma on ma.activity_id = a.activity_id where hash is null;
+----------+
| count(1) |
+----------+
|      400 |
+----------+
1 row in set (0.01 sec)
{code}

{code}
mysql> select count(1) from sta_pr_activity a join sta_pr_merge_activity ma on ma.activity_id = a.activity_id where hash is not null;
+----------+
| count(1) |
+----------+
|    20866 |
+----------+
1 row in set (0.04 sec)
{code}

~2% of all pull requests has no merge activity.

it would be great if the notification emails sent by Bitbucket whenever a pull request changes could contain the operation in the subject.

this is an example of a current subject:
{noformat}
OA/onlinelib - Pull request #14: OA-809 mark expired and inactive users
{noformat}

i think it would be nice if it could look like this:
{noformat}
OA/onlinelib - Pull request #14 [approved]: OA-809 mark expired and inactive users
{noformat}

maybe there could be all possible status changes in there (approved, declined, merged and new or nothing at all if a pull request was just created).

